# Project Rules — RideCompare PWA

## What this is
A Progressive Web App whose single job is to get the user from "I need a ride"
to a pre-filled Uber/Lyft booking in the fewest possible taps. It does NOT show
prices. It builds deep links that open each rideshare app with pickup
and destination already filled in. The price comparison happens in the native
apps after they open pre-filled — our value is eliminating the typing.

## Stack (do not change without being asked)
- Vite + React + TypeScript
- vite-plugin-pwa for manifest + service worker
- Tailwind CSS for styling
- Google Maps JavaScript API: Places Autocomplete + Geocoding + a route preview
- Deployed to Vercel; one serverless function in /api to proxy Google calls
- No state-management library (Redux/Zustand/etc.) — React state is enough
- No extra dependencies without asking first

## Why TypeScript
The core data model is location bundles {lat, lng, address} flowing through
builder functions into deep links. The app's single most likely bug is a
malformed/half-populated location object reaching a link builder (e.g. missing
the address string Uber requires, or mixing up Lyft's destination[] vs Uber's
dropoff[]). Types catch this at compile time instead of on the phone. Define a
Location type and use it everywhere.

## Security (hard rules)
- The Google Maps API key NEVER appears in client code. It lives only in the
  Vercel serverless function (/api), read from an environment variable.
- No analytics, no tracking, no third-party scripts beyond Google Maps.
- Favorites and recent destinations are stored ON-DEVICE only (localStorage).
  Never send the user's location history anywhere.

## Core data type (use everywhere)
```ts
type Location = {
  lat: number;
  lng: number;
  address: string;        // formatted street address from Places — REQUIRED
};
type Favorite = Location & { label: string };  // e.g. "Home", "Work"
```
A location is only valid once it has all three fields. Favorites add a label.

## Architecture rules
- Deep link construction is done in PURE FUNCTIONS that take a Location for
  pickup and a Location for dropoff and return a URL string. One per service.
- Services are an array of objects so adding a service later is trivial:
  { name, brandColor, buildUrl(pickup, dropoff) }. No hardcoded two-service
  assumptions scattered through the UI.
- URL-encode every value placed into a deep link.
- Build in vertical slices: each step must run and be testable on a real phone
  before moving on. Do not scaffold the whole app at once.

## The address-entry pattern (the heart of the UX)
A single focused field does double duty:
- When focused and EMPTY: show a dropdown list, in this order —
  1. Favorites (heart icon) — Home, Work, custom
  2. Recents (clock icon) — last ~6 destinations
- The moment the user TYPES: replace that list with Google Places autocomplete
  predictions.
- Favorites and recents must be visually distinct (heart vs clock icon) so the
  groups parse at a glance.

## Favorites creation (handle the address requirement correctly)
- A favorite is created THROUGH Places autocomplete, never from a bare map tap.
  Flow: tap heart -> small sheet -> type a label + search address via
  autocomplete -> save the full {label, lat, lng, address} bundle.
- Reason: we need the formatted street address string (for Uber's required
  dropoff[formatted_address]) AND coordinates (for Lyft). A map-tap gives
  coordinates with no reliable street address. Autocomplete-in, full-bundle-out.
- Favorites are NOT shown on the main page — only inside the field's dropdown.

## Pickup defaults
- Pickup defaults to current location via the Geolocation API on load, silently.
  The user usually never touches the start field.
- Current location gives lat/lng but NO street address. That's fine:
  - Uber: use pickup=my_location (no address needed).
  - Lyft: pickup lat/lng alone is fine.
  We therefore never need to reverse-geocode. Destination always has an address
  (it comes from autocomplete or a favorite), which is the only place Uber
  requires one.

## Confirmation map (after input, not before)
- After both pickup and dropoff are set, show a route PREVIEW map: draw the
  polyline pickup -> dropoff, fit bounds, done. Its purpose is letting the user
  confirm Google picked the right place before launching a ride.
- The two service buttons appear instantly alongside the preview — momentum.
- Keep it a PREVIEW: no draggable pins, no live traffic, no turn-by-turn. It is
  a confidence check, not the primary navigation surface. Speed beats decoration.

## Efficiency target
- Best case: 2 taps (tap a favorite/recent chip in the dropdown -> tap a service).
- Worst case: type a destination, glance at the route preview, tap a service.

## Code style
- Keep components small and readable. Prefer clarity over cleverness.
- Use window.location.href or a real <a href> to fire deep links — NOT
  window.open() (it can spawn an in-app browser tab that handles app schemes
  poorly inside a standalone PWA).
